<br>
And now, the update.  This will likely be the last update that I post to this thread, since the post-surgery news will be a while from now:<br>
<br>
July 28: Thanks to the many kind and generous people that have chosen to help a little black cat that they didn't even know, Sage is now going to be able to have her surgery.  When I was finally able to catch up with Elena this evening (I had to take one of my cats to the vet as well, and our schedules just didn't mesh as conveniently as they could have...) she gave me the wonderful news that Sage's PayPal fund had reached $1076.11, so I am taking down the link for contributions.  The surgery itself is quoted at $1030, but complications could raise the price by as much as $200, and we're hoping that the auctions (which are still linked on Sage's page) will raise enough money to cover this.  If there is money left over after the operation, it will either be used to cover Sage's post-operative care or left in trust at the veterinarian's office for the next person who has an emergency and can't pay their bill.<br>
<br>
I will continue to post updates on Sage's page about her health and the progress of her surgery, so that everyone can see what their generosity helped to accomplish.  Don't forget to look at the auctions if you can, which are still running, and check the page when you can for the latest news.  I think it's remarkable that so many people from so many different places were able to band together and accomplish something like this... it makes me feel a little bit better about the times that I wished I could have helped a friend or loved one but just didn't have the means.  The internet may cause problems for some people, and for others it can be a nuisance, but for Sage it has meant the difference between life and death, and I'm sure if she knew what was going on she would be grateful.  As for me, it has restored much of my faith in the strangers that sit on the other side of that internet connection, and in humanity in general...<br>
<br>
